The Data¶

In this project, we will be working with the Breast Cancer Wisconsin dataset, which contains 569 examples of malignant and benign tumor cells.
The Breast Cancer Wisconsin dataset can be found in the UCI Machine Learning Repository, and more detailed information about this dataset can be found at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Breast+Cancer+Wisconsin+(Diagnostic).
The first two columns in the dataset store the unique ID numbers of the examples and the corresponding diagnoses (M = malignant, B = benign), respectively.
Columns 3-32 contain 30 real-valued features that have been computed from digitized images of the cell nuclei, which can be used to build a model to predict whether a tumor is benign or malignant.

  • Make predictions

Method 1: Stratified Cross-Validation¶

  • To split the original train set to avoid overfitting and information leakage, so the model will accurately evaluated in each training
  • We should do Stratified Cross-Validation on the train set to ensure all the labels are equally represented.
  • Stratified Cross-Validation provides better accuracy which the variance is lower, so it is better than a single train test split and ensure the proper representation of each class
  • To find the best hyper-parameter for log-regression, the model will fit with Stratified 5-folds Cross-validation with the logistic regression using the same parameters and the same standardized X value like Question 11.
  • The comparision on both models are shown below.
In [66]:
# Standarized the X first, then initialized 5-fold Stratified Cross-Validation
ss = preprocessing.StandardScaler()
X_ss = ss.fit_transform(X_train).tolist()
skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, random_state=40)
skf.get_n_splits(X_ss, y_train)

5
In [67]:
# Hyper-parameter tuning with 5-fold Stratified Cross-Validation
# The accuracy scores are the mean accuracy from each fold
C_list = [0.0001, 0.0005, 0.001, 0.005, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.5, 1, 2, 10, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000]
accuracy_valid = []
for C in C_list:
    clf = LogisticRegression(max_iter = 10000, solver='lbfgs', penalty='l2', C=C)
    score_valid= cross_val_score(clf,X_ss, y_train, scoring = "accuracy", cv =skf )
    accuracy_valid.append(score_valid.mean())

  • The model in Question 11 that we used only 1 train/test split to fit the model. The model in question 11 has an unreliable behavior as the accuracy scores of train and test sets in Q 11 stay constant after C > 10.

Method 2: Select the best features to fit model¶

  • To avoid overfitting and improve the model accuracy, we need to select important features that have the strongest relationship with the the target class
  • Use ExtraTreesClassifier to examine the important value of features
  • The higher value is the more important the variable is.
  • We will drop features with the low feature importances scores

Comparing the new model to the original model (30 vs 23 features)¶

  • The model with 30 features have some features are not significantly related to the target variable and can lead to overfit model.

Conclusion:¶

  • Both proposed methods: Stratified Cross validation and Feature Selection help improve the performance of model in reducing the overfitting effect and finding the optimal value of hyper parameter.
  • The Stratified Cross validation solves the imbalanced class problem of the target variable in which it ensures the equal proportion of target class for each fold.
  • The feature selection also improved the model as we eliminate the unimportant/irrelevent features that not contribute to predict the target class.
